featured_reviews.review_id:
Jama Masjid, a magnificent embodiment of Mughal architecture, graces the heart of Delhi, India. Commissioned by the illustrious Emperor Shah Jahan and completed in 1656, this grand mosque stands as a testament to the opulence and artistic finesse of the Mughal dynasty. With its colossal courtyard, the mosque can accommodate a staggering multitude of worshippers, reflecting its vital role as a religious center.

The mosque's striking facade boasts red sandstone and marble intricately adorned with delicate calligraphy, geometric patterns, and floral motifs. Its three imposing domes rise elegantly above the landscape, while two towering minarets on either side add to the mosque's visual splendor and provide panoramic views of the city.

Stepping into the courtyard, visitors are engulfed by a sense of serenity amidst the bustling city. The central pool, used for ablutions, mirrors the awe-inspiring architecture and adds a tranquil touch. The prayer hall, a cavernous expanse, showcases stunning prayer niches and marble floors that radiate an air of devotion and reverence.

Jama Masjid stands as a living historical monument, a spiritual haven, and a cultural emblem, drawing people from diverse backgrounds to witness its grandeur and experience its spiritual resonance. It preserves the legacy of the Mughal era and remains an enduring symbol of India's rich heritage and religious harmony.

featured_reviews.review_id:
I am a fan of authentic South Indian food and after spending some good time in southern part of our country i always look out for similar taste.

With not much hope visited this place for a casual lunch which turned out to be a lip smacking experience.

Ordered:
Paper masala dosa, Masala dosa, Masala Chajj and
Dahi wada.

Though they took ages to serve the food even though it wasn't much occupied but the food they served made me forgot everything. It was a very welcome surprise.

They served the Dahi wada first and it was as perfect as it could get. The green chilly and tomato on the top was like a teaser for the taste buds.

The masala chajj/ Lassi as we call it here was Hot ( spicy ) but that's how i like it to be !

They serve their dosas with 3 different chutneys/ sauce:
Coconut, red and green. I generally don't try anything other than coconut chutney but their taste was different and i ended up asking for round two of green and the red ones ;)

They did surprised me and will be my regular place to visit for sure.

Highly recommended for their south Indian food.

featured_reviews.review_id: Went out there with family for an easy dinner on a fine Saturday evening. The place was teeming with people. Had to wait for 5 minutes outside the place standing. The place is located on ground floor of Greater Kailash M-Block market. Luckily, we were able to find parking just opposite the restaurant. There are four stair steps that one has to climb, though side railing is there for support but a little pavement before it can be hindrance for people who walk with calipers and walking stick like myself. The place is NOT wheel chair accessible like most of our Indian food joints. People spend crores on embellishments but don't spend iota of their time Or brains on making these places inclusive for a sizable #disabled population of India. However this disabled population is called Divyang. The furniture could have been more comfortable. The tables are okay, made of brass. The chairs are hard. The decor is good. Since it's almost end of October, the atmosphere was cosy. The staff was courteous and service fast. All the items were  prepared in pure ghee. The dosas are served with three kinds of chutneys. I personally liked original coconut chutney. The Dahi vada was sweet.The malleshwaram dosa will make you remember parantha made of homemade ghee residue. I found it awesome. The ghee roast dosa is served with potato masala on the side NOT inside. One has to ask for saambar, they don't serve suo motu. The podu are fried idlis like balls. The kesri bath was like light suji halwa. Generally, you feel hungry after an hour or two when you have had South Indian meal. However, this is the first instance when I felt full even when going to bed. Worth giving a try once. You won't regret it. All the same, I would prefer dosa in Lal Sai Market, Lajpat Nagar anytime over any upscale restaurant in Delhi. Street food beats restaurants all the times.

I visited Carnatic Cafe with high hopes of indulging in some authentic South Indian cuisine, given its reputation as one of Delhi's best South-Indian restaurants. Regrettably, my experience fell short of expectations. I ordered their masala dosa, rava masala dosa, and kesari bath, only to be disappointed by the excessive oiliness in the dishes. The masala dosa, in particular, left me astounded as oil seemed to overflow with every bite. Furthermore, the kesari bath lacked the expected flavor, resembling nothing more than rava soaked in an abundance of oil. Even their sambar was below average.

In my opinion, Carnatic Cafe may be somewhat overhyped and fails to justify a visit. Delhi now has a variety of South Indian eateries that surpass this one.

Overall, its a great experience whenever you visit this place.

-Tandoori chicken
- Khameeri roti

featured_reviews.review_id: Have visited many Mac D's in Delhi , however this one at the Chandani chowk was unique. It was as crowded as the market itself. Wanted to have quick clean bite and my friend opted for a clean n hygienic place rather the oily choley batture which we normally have post the covid thing. Even though the place was crowed, the staff was managing it well. The tables were not restricted to a specific group or family , even if a single seat was vacant the staff would ensure its get occupied and no one is standing with his/her tray of food. Could see the kitchen and the staff was wearing gloves and mask. Enjoyed our chicken maharaja combo with peri peri fries and Pepsi. (in our opinion Mac D shouldn't have charged extra for the peri peri recipe) said that, it was filling delicious meal. enjoyed it to the last bite.
